{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563742"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:04:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:04:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16872"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.25,0.51,0.03,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105080"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4356"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105080"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the labour ward at 37 weeks gestation with regular uterine contractions every three minutes. This is her first pregnancy, a dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancy confirmed on early ultrasound scans. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy supplements. Pregnancy has been uncomplicated thus far and the twins are normally grown. Both twins are in cephalic presentation with Twin 1 engaged. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals regular strong contractions. Vaginal examination reveals her cervix is 4 cm dilated, fully effaced, and membranes intact. Cardiotocography shows reassuring traces for both twins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate recommended management to discuss with this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxytocin augmentation","Artificial rupture of membranes","Expectant management with intermittent monitoring","Immediate caesarean section","Epidural analgesia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents in established labour with a dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancy at term. Both twins are cephalic, which allows for attempted vaginal delivery, but twin pregnancies carry higher risks of complications and operative delivery compared to singleton pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidural analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended early in labour for twin pregnancies when there is a plan for a vaginal birth. This is because twin deliveries have a higher risk of requiring intrapartum manoeuvres (internal podalic version or instrumental deliveries) and emergency caesarean section. Having an epidural in place allows for rapid conversion to surgical anaesthesia if needed. It also provides excellent pain relief during labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case as both twins are cephalic, the labour is progressing normally, and both fetal heart traces are reassuring. Vaginal delivery can be safely attempted in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArtificial rupture of membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage as labour is progressing normally. Breaking the membranes could increase the risk of cord prolapse, particularly in a multiple pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin augmentation\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the labour is progressing normally with strong regular contractions. Twin pregnancies often progress more rapidly than singleton pregnancies and augmentation may increase the risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management with intermittent monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as continuous cardiotocography monitoring is required for both twins throughout labour due to the increased risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of twin labour requires close monitoring and preparation for potential complications. Other important aspects include ensuring appropriate staff (obstetrician, anaesthetist, paediatrician) are readily available and that facilities for emergency caesarean section are prepared.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early epidural analgesia is recommended for twin pregnancies in labour to facilitate emergency caesarean section if required.","Twin pregnancies have a higher risk of operative delivery and emergency caesarean section compared to singleton pregnancies.","Continuous cardiotocography monitoring is required for both twins during labour."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Twin and triplet pregnancy [Internet]. London: NICE; 2019 [cited 2024 Dec 4]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng137/resources/twin-and-triplet-pregnancy-pdf-66141724389829."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisio